@Node "Exit.dat"
@Next "Extra.dat"
@Prev "Editor"
@Toc "Main"

                         @{b}@{u}Location for the exit@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Exit.dat

Needed tool(s)    : Text Editor    (GoldED, SygnusED, etc...)
                    Paint Program  (DPaint, PPaint, Brilliance, etc...)


The file @{b}Exit.dat@{ub} contain the @{" coordinates " Link Coordinates} of the top-left point(s)
of the exit-object(s). The exit will be placed on one of these
coordinates. Use a Paint Program to find the right coordinates.
You must first draw a @{" Landscape " Link Map.iff}. You need to end this list
with @{b}999@{ub}.


Example:

      x   y
   ---------
    542 419
    326  54
    304  54
     58 496
      .   .
      .   .
      .   .
    999



@EndNode

@Node "Extra.dat"
@Next "Fuel.dat"
@Prev "Exit.dat"
@Toc "Main"

                        @{b}@{u}Location for the stars@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Extra.dat

Needed tool(s)    : Text Editor    (GoldED, SygnusED, etc...)
                    Paint Program  (DPaint, PPaint, Brilliance, etc...)


The file @{b}Extra.dat@{ub} contain the @{" coordinates " Link Coordinates} of the top-left point(s)
of the star(s). The star(s) will be placed on one of these coordinates.
Use a Paint Program to find the right coordinates. You must first draw
a @{" Landscape " Link Map.iff}. You need to end this list with @{b}999@{ub}.


Example:

      x   y
   ---------
     53 490
    128 490
    337 490
     38 336
      .   .
      .   .
      .   .
    999

@EndNode

@Node "Fuel.dat"
@Next "Location.dat"
@Prev "Extra.dat"
@Toc "Main"

                            @{b}@{u}Fuel-locations@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Fuel_car.dat
                    Fuel_man.dat
                    Fuel_pln.dat

Needed tool(s)    : Text Editor    (GoldED, SygnusED, etc...)
                    Paint Program  (DPaint, PPaint, Brilliance, etc...)


The files: @{b}Fuel_car.dat@{ub}, @{b}Fuel_man.dat@{ub} and @{b}Fuel_pln.dat@{ub} contain the
@{" coordinates " Link Coordinates} of the top-left and bottem-right point(s) of the places
where fuel can be collected. On all of these coordinates fuel can be found.
Use a Paint Program to find the right coordinates. You must first draw a 
@{" Landscape " Link Map.iff}. You need to end this list with @{b}999@{ub}.


Example:

     x1  y1  x2  y2
   -----------------
    316 139 332 128
    587 454 603 443
      .   .   .   .
      .   .   .   .
      .   .   .   .
    999

@EndNode

@Node "Location.dat"
@Next "Map.dat"
@Prev "Fuel.dat"
@Toc "Main"

                           @{b}@{u}Start-locations@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Loc_car.dat
                    Loc_man.dat
                    Loc.pln.dat

Needed tool(s)    : Text Editor    (GoldED, SygnusED, etc...)
                    Paint Program  (DPaint, PPaint, Brilliance, etc...)


The files @{b}Loc_car.dat@{ub}, @{b}Loc_man.dat@{ub} and @{b}Loc_pln.dat@{ub} contain the
@{" coordinates " Link Coordinates} of the top-left point(s) of the vehicles. The vehicles
will be placed on one of these coordinates. Use a Paint Program to
find the right coordinates. You must first draw a @{" Landscape " Link Map.iff}.
You need to end this list with @{b}999@{ub}. As shown below there's also a
value: d. This d stands for @{" direction " Link Direction}.

Example:


      x   y   d
   -------------
     26 459   7
     26 442   7
    245 403   1
    531 145   7
      .   .   .
      .   .   .
      .   .   .
    999

@EndNode

@Node "Map.dat"
@Next "Map.iff"
@Prev "Location.dat"
@Toc "Main"

                            @{b}@{u}Object-locations@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Map.dat

Needed tool(s)    : Text Editor    (GoldED, SygnusED, etc...)
                    Paint Program  (DPaint, PPaint, Brilliance, etc...)


The file: @{b}Map.dat@{ub} contain the @{" coordinates " Link Coordinates} of the top-left and
bottem-right point(s) of the places where the man and car cannot
travel (buildings, fences, etc.) . Use a Paint Program to find the
right coordinates. You must first draw a @{" Landscape " Link Map.iff}. You need
to end this list with @{b}999@{ub}.


Example:

     x1  y1  x2  y2
   -----------------
    239 311 325 239
    245 210 260 202
    274 210 289 202
      0 371  95 368
      .   .   .   .
      .   .   .   .
      .   .   .   .
    999

@EndNode

@Node "Map.iff"
@Next "Editor"
@Prev "Map.dat"
@Toc "Main"

                             @{b}@{u}The landscape@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Map.iff

Needed tool(s)    : Paint Program  (DPaint, PPaint, Brilliance, etc...)


This is the most difficult part. You've got to draw a landscape using
a Paint Program and @{b}must@{ub} use the @{" palette " Link Editor} used in the original
landscape-file..

If you need an example, you can look at the original landscape stored
in the ../program/landscape drawer.

@EndNode

@Node "Editor"
@Next "Exit.dat"
@Prev "Map.iff"
@Toc "Main"

                            @{b}@{u}Protected files@{ub}@{uu}


Landscape-file(s) : Map.pal
                    Shapes.dat

Needed tool(s)    : None


These files cannot be changed when using the @{" unregistered version " Link Register} of
Marathon (sorry). They contain all the objects used in the game and
the palette which is used for these. You will have to copy these two
files (stored in the ../program/landscape drawer).

@EndNode


