@Node "Coordinates"
@Next "Coordinates"
@Prev "Coordinates"
@Toc "Main"

                              @{b}@{u}Coordinates@{ub}@{uu}


The size of a landscape is 640*512 (a standard hires-lace screen).
The screen looks like:

                          ___________________
              (y =) 512  |                   |
                      .  |                   |
                      .  |                   |
                      .  |     LANDSCAPE     |
                      .  |                   |
                      .  |                   |
                      .  |                   |
                         |                   |
                      0  |___________________|

                         0 . . . . . . . 640 (= x)


The textfile you are creating is used to place the objects.
@EndNode

; -----

@Node "Direction"
@Next "Direction"
@Prev "Direction"
@Toc "Main"

                               @{b}@{u}Direction@{ub}@{uu}


Vehicles (including the man) can look at 24 different directions.
Each direction has it's own value, these are as follows:


                                  1

                                  |
                                  |
                               .  |  2
                             .    |    3
                           .      |      4
                         .        |        5
                       .          |          6
                  19 -------------+-------------- 7
                       .          |          .
                         .        |        .
                           .      |      .
                             .    |    .
                               .  |  .
                                  |
                                  |

                                 13

Example:

A car pointing north (up) has a value: 1
@EndNode

; --------


@Node "Winning"
@Next "Difficulty"
@Prev "Exit"
@Toc "Main"

                            @{b}@{u}Winning the game@{ub}@{uu}


You win the game by collecting four (4) stars and reach the exit
before the other player does. These stars are located somewhere on the
landscape. Only one star at the time is available. Sometimes, depending 
what @{" difficulty-level " Link Difficulty} you are playing you are forced to kill your
opponent to get all four (4) stars. Killing your opponent will decrease
the number of stars by one (1). This star will be placed somewhere on
the landscape which can be collected by one of the two players.
@EndNode


@Node "Difficulty"
@Next "Stuff"
@Prev "Winning"
@Toc "Main"

                         @{b}@{u}About difficulty-levels@{ub}@{uu}


There are three difficulty-levels. Each level will affect the number
of stars found on the landscape. As you have probably noticed, this
can be a problem when playing the @{b}normal@{ub} and @{b}hard@{ub} level, because
there are not enough stars for both players. The levels can be
changed in the game-menu screen. The following levels are available:


    Difficulty-level    Number of stars
   -------------------------------------
    Easy                Unlimited
    Normal              six (6)
    Hard                four (4)





@EndNode



@Node "Stuff"
@Next "Vehicles"
@Prev "Difficulty"
@Toc "Main"

                        @{b}@{u}How to get what you need@{ub}@{uu}


There are a couple of things you might want to collect during the
game, like stars, the exit, fuel (including food) and a car/plane.


@{i}Stars:@{ui}

Collecting stars is easy. Just walk over them and they are yours.
If you are inside a car or plane you need to get out first.


@{i}The exit:@{ui}

The same way as the stars. You need four stars before you can go
through though.


@{i}Fuel:@{ui}

All vehicles need fuel (even the man (food)). Collecting fuel
can be done by walking, driving or flying towards a fuel-deposite.
Each vehicle has its own place to get fuel. Before getting fuel
you need to stand still on top of the fuel-deposite.


@{i}Cars and planes:@{ui}

If you would like to use a car or plane, you need to walk to them
and press the joystick-button.

@{b}Do not try to get into a moving car !!!@{ub}
@EndNode


@Node "Vehicles"
@Next "Radar"
@Prev "Stuff"
@Toc "Main"

                          @{b}@{u}About the vehicles@{ub}@{uu}


There are three (3) different kind of vehicles. Each of them with
its own advantages and disadvantages.


@{i}1. Man:@{ui}

The man is the slowest of the three, but is the only one able to
shoot down planes (real fast too!). When you are good enough it's
also a good way to dispose of cars. This is especially handy when
the car is out of gas. Shooting it will result in a new car,
somewhere on the landscape. The man is also the only one which
can get stars and go through the exit. Speed and the possiblity
of being run over by a car are its weak points though.


@{i}2. Car:@{ui}

The car is, while using the turbo the fastest thing around. Press
your joystick-button during driving to activate your turbo. The
turbo costs a lot of fuel though, so please be careful. Driving
the car is for experienced people only (especially when using
the turbo). This because driving against fences and other
obstacles will quickly result in an explosion. Cars are the
strongest of the three, although energy and fuel can sometimes
be very low, even at the start.


@{i}3. Plane:@{ui}

Only one plane is available. The plane is weak but much faster
than walking and is the only thing able to fly over buildings.
Its greatest threat is being shot down. Please watch your fuel
too, it will be gone before you know it.
@EndNode


@Node "Radar"
@Next "Exit"
@Prev "Vehicles"
@Toc "Main"

                             @{b}@{u}Use your radar@{ub}@{uu}


Using the radar can be very handy. It shows you what vehicle is
close (even those which cannot be seen on your screen). The
colours used are:

     Vehicle          Colour
    -------------------------
     You              White
     Opponent         Yellow
     Empty car        Blue
     Empty plane      Red


@EndNode



@Node "Exit"
@Next "Winning"
@Prev "Radar"
@Toc "Main"

                             @{b}@{u}Exit the game@{ub}@{uu}


While playing hit @{b}escape@{ub} to abandon the game.

You can return to the workbench by changing @{b}start game@{ub} into @{b}no@{ub} and
press the joystick-button.

@EndNode




